Your CPU runs in one of two relevant privilege levels. On x86-64 these are **ring 0** (kernel mode) and **ring 3** (user mode); other ISAs have analogous EL1/EL0 or supervisor/user modes. In ring 3 your code cannot touch hardware directly, cannot reprogram the MMU, and cannot execute privileged instructions — the same protection scheme you knew on radar hardware where only privileged firmware could poke certain registers. Everything else (browsers, compilers, your daemon) lives in ring 3.

When user code needs something only the kernel may do — read a file, allocate memory, send a packet — it cannot just jump into kernel code. That would defeat isolation. Instead it executes a **trap**: a single controlled instruction (`syscall` on x86-64, `svc` on ARM) that switches the CPU to ring 0 at *one fixed kernel entry point*. The kernel decides what to do based on a number you placed in a register.

```c
/* No stdio. A raw syscall: number in rax, args in rdi/rsi/rdx. */
#include <unistd.h>
int main(void) {
    write(1, "hi\n", 3);   /* __NR_write = 1 on x86-64 */
    return 0;
}
```

The argument count and order is the **syscall calling convention**, distinct from the C calling convention. The gateway is narrow on purpose: a fixed entry, a validated syscall number, and arguments the kernel must treat as untrusted. This single boundary — cross it deliberately or not at all — is the conceptual core of how Linux stays safe from the millions of lines of code running above it.

```bash
strace -e trace=write ./a.out   # see the one write() crossing the line
```

Behind the gateway the kernel is a multiplexer for shared resources. The big services it provides: **process scheduling** (deciding which thread runs on which CPU), **memory management** (virtual memory, paging, and the MMU translating per-process virtual addresses to physical frames — the same address-translation idea as a hardware page table), the **VFS** (one `open/read/write` interface over ext4, XFS, procfs, NFS, …), the **network stack** (TCP/IP, sockets), and **device drivers** that own the actual hardware.

You rarely issue raw `syscall` instructions. The **C library** (glibc on most distros, musl on Alpine/embedded) is a thin wrapper: `read()` in your code is a tiny libc stub that marshals arguments into registers, executes the trap, and converts the kernel's return into a C-friendly value plus `errno`. libc also adds buffering (stdio's `fread`), which is why one `printf` may not equal one `write`.

```c
#include <fcntl.h>
#include <unistd.h>
int fd = open("data.bin", O_RDONLY);   /* open + read + close: 3 syscalls */
char buf[4096];
ssize_t n = read(fd, buf, sizeof buf);
close(fd);
```

Distinguish **API** from **ABI**. The API is the source-level contract (function names, header types) you compile against. The **ABI** is the binary contract: which register holds which argument, struct layouts, the syscall numbers themselves. Linux famously keeps a stable syscall ABI — an old binary keeps working — even as APIs evolve.

Key syscall families to recognize: **process** (`fork`, `execve`, `wait4`, `exit`, `clone` — `clone` underlies both threads and container namespaces); **file** (`open`, `read`, `write`, `close`, `lseek`, `stat`, `mmap`); **IPC/sync** (`pipe`, `socket`, `shmget`, `futex` — the primitive under mutexes); **signals** (`kill`, `sigaction`, `rt_sigprocmask`).

```bash
strace -e trace=%process ./launcher   # watch fork/execve/wait4/clone
```
